\par
\pard\li360\f0 This program allows almost all modified Starcraft data files to be loaded from Starcraft maps instead of just preloaded mpq archives.\f1\par
\par
\pard\ul\b\f0\fs24 Creating a map for use with this program\ulnone\b0\f1\fs20\par
\pard\li360\f0 1) Create a Starcraft map.  You may want to add a note somewhere in the map that it needs SCMLoader for using all of the maps features and give my site address somewhere.\par
\par
2) Add modified Starcraft data files to your map with your favorite MPQ archiver.\par
\par
\pard\ul\b\fs24 Using SCMLoader\ulnone\b0\f1\fs20\par
\pard\li360\f0 1) Run SCMLoader.exe\par
\par
2) When Starcraft is loaded, open your map containing the modified files to see the effects.\i\par
\i0\par
\pard\ul\b\fs24 Using the SCMLoader plugin with MPQDraft\ulnone\b0\f1\fs20\par
\pard\li360\f0 1) Load MPQDraft, select Starcraft, and on the plugin screen add SCMLoader.qdp to the list and make sure it has a check by it, then click "Finish."\par
\par
2) When Starcraft is loaded, open your map containing the modified files to see the effects.\i\par
\i0\par
\i Note:  This plugin may also be used in the Campaign Editor, but to a lesser extent.  I recommend instead adding the modified files to a separate mpq archive and using MPQDraft to load that to use the modified data files while making your map.\par
\i0\par
\pard\ul\b\fs24 Creating all-in-one mod exe files\ulnone\b0\f1\fs20\par
\pard\li360\f0 1) Add SCMLoader.qdp to your mod MPQ archive.\par
\par
2) Make a copy of SCMLoader.exe and give the copy an appropriate name.\par
\par
3) Use MPQ Embedder (available with WinMPQ or as a separate program) to open the copy of SCMLoader.exe that you made in step 2.\par
\par
4) Click the Add button and when prompted open up your mod MPQ archive to attach it to the exe.\par
\par
The exe file you have just packaged with your mod can be used to launch StarCraft with your modifications or load your mod into StarCraft when SCMLoader is already running.\par
\par
\pard\ul\b\fs24 Using SCMLoader for single-player campaign maps\ulnone\b0\f1\fs20\par
\pard\li360\f0 1) Add your map uncompressed to your mod MPQ archive at the location for a campaign map.  For example, if the campaign map was campaign\\expprotoss\\protoss01\\staredit\\scenario.chk then add your map at campaign\\expprotoss\\protoss01.scx\par
The file extension can be either scm or scx.  SCMLoader with check for either.\par
\par
2) Load your mod with SCModLoader or use a separate mod loader and use the SCMLoader plugin with it.  When playing that campaign map, SCMLoader will direct StarCraft to your included scm/scx file and load any mods that are included in it. (each campaign map can have its own set of modified files)\par
\par
\pard\ul\b\fs24 Using MPQ packs\ulnone\b0\f1\fs20\par
\pard\li360\f0 1) Create an MPQ archive with modified data files for Starcraft.  In practice these should only be files which do not affect gameplay and that would not cause players to be dropped if some players do not have the MPQ pack.  Basically, any files that you want to be just optional.\par
\par
2) Create a list of the optional MPQ archives and add it to your Starcraft map as mpqpacks\\mpqlist.txt with an MPQ archiver.  Do not include any absolute paths in the list, they will not work; however, you may include any type of relative path that you wish to use.\par
\par
By default, the MPQ archives will be loaded with priority under the scm/scx, meaning that the scm/scx will be checked for the modified files first before the MPQ archive.  A plus sign "+" may be added to the beginning of the line to boost priority over the scm/scx.  For MPQ archives with the same type of priority, the one further down in the list will have higher priority.\par
\par
SCMLoader will by default look for the MPQ archives in the same folder as SCMLoader.  To have it look in the Starcraft folder instead, add a pipe character "|" to the beginning of the name.  To have it look in the same folder as the map, add an "at" symbol "@" to the beginning of the name.  To load the archive from any open archive, place a colon ":" before the MPQ path (useful for campaign maps with mods shared between only a portion of the maps).  Any of these go immediately after the plus sign "+" if it is being used.\par
\par
A sample mpqpacks\\mpqlist.txt file demonstrating several of the different ways that the MPQ list may be set up:\par
\par
\f2 |Stardat.mpq\par
|Broodat.mpq\par
|patch_rt.mpq\par
My mpq1.mpq\par
folder\\My mpq2.mpq\par
+@My mpq3.mpq\par
@My mpq4.mpq\par
+My mpq5.mpq\par
|My mpq6.mpq\par
:mods\\My mpq7.mpq\i\f0\par
\i0\par
For this example, if Starcraft was installed to "C:\\Starcraft" and SCMLoader was extracted to "C:\\SCMLoader" and SCMLoader was loaded through MPQDraft along with an mpq archive named "mpqdraft patch.mpq" and a map named "My map.scm" is loaded from "C:\\Starcraft\\maps" , when Starcraft requests a file from an MPQ archive, they will be checked in this order and will have these paths (where full paths are shown):\par
\par
\f2 C:\\SCMLoader\\My mpq5.mpq\par
C:\\Starcraft\\maps\\My mpq3.mpq\par
C:\\Starcraft\\maps\\My map.scm\par
mods\\My mpq7.mpq (opened from another open MPQ)\par
C:\\Starcraft\\My mpq6.mpq\par
C:\\Starcraft\\maps\\My mpq4.mpq\par
C:\\SCMLoader\\folder\\My mpq2.mpq\par
C:\\SCMLoader\\My mpq1.mpq\par
C:\\Starcraft\\patch_rt.mpq\par
C:\\Starcraft\\Broodat.mpq\par
C:\\Starcraft\\Stardat.mpq\par
mpqdraft patch.mpq\par
C:\\Starcraft\\patch_rt.mpq\par
C:\\Starcraft\\Broodat.mpq\par
C:\\Starcraft\\Stardat.mpq\par
(CD drive letter):\\Install.exe\f0\par
\par
Notice that the last archive with a "+" by it was the first checked, then the next one above it with a plus.  After that is the map, then all of the archives in the list without a "+ by them in order from last to first.  After that are any archives loaded by MPQDraft, then the four archives that are always loaded by Starcraft Brood War.  By adding those first three lines to the MPQ list, you can make it so that only your own modified files get used with your map when it is being used with SCMLoader.\par
\pard\f1\par
